http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-trade "TPP FOR TENNESSEE: The heavily Republican state, home to the Nashville music industry and a major exporter of Jack Daniel’s whiskey and other distilled spirits, is a perfect example of how the agreement will benefit a broad cross-section of the U.S. economy, Froman argued.  “Tennessee has about 150,000 people whose jobs are tied to exports and it’s really across the board. It’s autos and auto parts, ag products like soybeans and wheat, but also distilled spirits. Then on the services side, certainly music is a huge export for them,” Froman said. “When you talk to people who are writing music or people who are trying to export Tennessee whiskey and the choice is we either eliminate our tariffs and put in place our IP [intellectual property] rules or we let the EU send its whiskey to Vietnam at a preferential rate and let China define the IP rules, it underscores just how much is at stake in getting this done now.” "TPP’S UNEXPECTED FOE: As if TPP didn’t have enough problems, the Obama administration will face an unexpected adversary as it gears up for what could be a blockbuster lame-duck fight over the trade pact: the Black Lives Matter movement, POLITICO’s Andrew Hanna reports.  . . . [It]  has joined the fray over the Asian-Pacific trade deal as part of its growing focus on economic issues. It contends the pact would lead to greater racial injustice, tying past trade deals to closures of factories that have hurt black workers disproportionately in many areas and increased black poverty. "Black Lives Matters’ involvement could influence the votes of a handful of wavering Democrats, should Congress tackle TPP during the lame-duck. Only a small band of 28 House Democrats voted to give the president fast track authority to complete TPP, including three members of the Congressional Black Caucus: Reps. Gregory Meeks (D-N.Y.), Eddie Bernice Johnson (D-Texas) and Terri Sewell (D-Ala.). A fourth member of the caucus, Republican Mia Love of Utah, also voted for fast-track authority. Their votes are considered key to passing TPP — and all are under increasing pressure to abandon Obama should the pact come to a ratification vote. Read the full story here.
. . . 
"HUFBAUER ON TPP’S ‘PATH TO RESURRECTION’: The TPP is probably dead for the rest of the Obama administration, but that doesn’t mean it can’t rise again in one or two years, with a little goading from the other countries that are members of the pact, says Gary Hufbauer, a senior fellow at the Peterson Institute for International Economics.“ . . . " in 2018, 2019, she rediscovers the global security imperative for going with TPP and she gives it a new name. New coloration, new name, and the U.S. comes in. That’s the path to resurrection.” "Three-Card Monte? But former Commerce Under Secretary Grant Aldonas said he didn’t believe Clinton would be able to pull that move on voters. “Gary, what you just did is a little bit like three-card monte or a shell game,” Aldonas said. “The problem, I think, with this iteration of our populist politics is that they’ve actually seen that shell game before,” in terms of how President Bill Clinton tweaked NAFTA in 1993 to make it more palatable to Democrats.
Aldonas said one of the strongest arguments President Obama could make for approving TPP in the lame duck is that it would clear the deck for Clinton to make a fresh start with her own trade policy, but getting that done could require broadening the conversation to other issues, such as tax reform. “In some sense we have to widen the circle of people, because the people inside the circle deciding this issue don’t have enough votes to actually pass the agreement,” Aldonas said, expressing skepticism that Obama could pull that off.

www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-trade#ixzz4Ohp7Y86o  "“We’re doing all the preparatory work that we can, whether it’s meeting with individual members, working on outstanding issues, making sure that the [TPP implementing] bill and the reports and the statement of administrative action are all ready to go,” Froman said Friday, after talking up the pact in Nashville. “We have been very focused on doing all the things that are within our control to maximize the likelihood it gets approved in a lame duck.” ‘A pretty firm bunch’: The U.S. trade chief said he felt comfortable the 28 House Democrats and 13 Senate Democrats who voted last year for trade promotion authority would vote for TPP, with the exception of Sen. Tim Kaine, who came out against the pact when he became Hillary Clinton’s running mate. “I don’t think we can take anyone for granted, but I think they are a pretty firm bunch,” Froman said. "The White House also sees strong support on the other side of the aisle, Froman said, adding that he personally met with about 95 House Republicans who had some questions or nervousness about the agreement. “Those meetings, with very few exceptions, have gone extremely well. I think there’s a lot of support out there,” Froman said. “They all, of course, are attuned to the politics and want to understand when and how we’re going to bring it forward.”
In that regard, Froman said the Obama administration is working with Senate Finance Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch to address concerns lawmakers have raised. With the lame-duck session set to begin two weeks from today, the pressure is on for the White House to reach a deal that would persuade Republican leaders to schedule action on the pact.

Treaties, as I recall, must be ratified by a two-thirds vote in the Senate.  It is likely that this settles the hash of the TPP until after the new Congress sits and after each party manages to find some adults who can settle things.   On the D side there are a fair number of these, although heir apparent Chuck Schumer is not among them.  Durbin could take the lead on this and get it done on that side, especially since at this point the Ds are much less fragmented, as long as they don’t need Bernie’s vote.  Among the Rs, there are fewer candidates for the role of grownup.  McCain might return to his senses after he wins, as he probably will; and Ayotte is not crazy if she wins, as she probably won’t.  Collins is always good for This Sort of Thing; Alexander may not get the vapours at the thought of ratifying.  None of this, however, will occur before the 20th, and 67 votes is a lot.  May be a while.

After the election the Republican leadership may not have to worry about reelection for a couple of years, but they will have to worry about retaining their positions within their parties.   I think there is sufficient opposition within congressional ranks on both sides to prevent the leadership from trying to pass it.  As much as I want it to pass,  I don't think it will.  This is just too hot of an issue.  Congressional leadership won't pass it because they want to retain their leadership positions in 2017.  If Trans-Pacific is passed by Congress it will be after the new congress is sworn in.   If Trump wins, it will never pass.  But I don't think Trump will win.   So it's possible it will pass sometime in 2017, probably after some changes have been made to it.  The new congress will need some cover on this .

For generations, libraries full of economics textbooks have rightly promised that global trade expands national wealth by lowering the price of goods, lifting wages and amplifying growth. The powers that emerged victorious from World War II championed globalization as the antidote to future conflicts. In Asia, Europe and North America, governments of every ideological persuasion have focused on trade as their guiding economic force. But trade comes with no assurances that the spoils will be shared equitably. Across much of the industrialized world, an outsize share of the winnings have been harvested by people with advanced degrees, stock options and the need for accountants. Ordinary laborers have borne the costs and suffered from joblessness and deepening economic anxiety. These costs have proved overwhelming in communities that depend on industry for sustenance, vastly exceeding what economists anticipated. Policy makers under the thrall of neoliberal economic philosophy put stock in the notion that markets could be trusted to bolster social welfare. In doing so, they failed to plan for the trauma that has accompanied the benefits of trade. When millions of workers lost paychecks to foreign competition, they lacked government supports to cushion the blow. As a result, seething anger is upending politics in Europe and North America.
In the boundless strangeness of the universe, a great many things are possible.  This is not one of them.
